swift.instructions:
IMPORTANT: In Swift, files containing the @main attribute MUST NOT be named main.swift.

When the @main attribute is used (e.g., @main struct App), Swift automatically generates an entry point. If the file is also named main.swift, Swift treats it as having a manual entry point, causing a conflict.

RULES:
- Never name a file main.swift if it contains @main attribute
- Use descriptive names like App.swift, MyApp.swift, or the actual type name
- If you encounter a main.swift with @main, rename it to match the type (e.g., struct MyApp -> MyApp.swift)

EXAMPLES:

BAD:
```
// main.swift
@main
struct App {
    static func main() { ... }
}
```

GOOD:
```
// App.swift
@main
struct App {
    static func main() { ... }
}
```
